oc:kn_7a3678e7 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:RecoveryTactic ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When handling multi-contact engagement from named accounts" ;
    oc:directiveContent "When 3+ contacts from the same ABM target account engage, trigger a 'buying committee' alert to the account owner and track account-level engagement as the sum of all contact scores." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Multiple contacts engaging signals organizational buying intent; the owner needs visibility to coordinate outreach across stakeholders" ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_7b45b445 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing any routing decision tree" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Route to the most specific match first, then fall back to general assignment. Named/target accounts take priority, then ACV-based, then PLG, then territory, then round-robin default." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Specific matches (named accounts, high-value deals) require dedicated owners; generic catch-alls ensure no lead goes unassigned" ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_83856d8f a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When configuring territory routing" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never rely on a single routing dimension. Pure geography-only or size-only routing misses cross-dimensional edge cases like strategic accounts in SMB-sized companies or vertical specialists needed for specific industries." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Hybrid models combining company size, geography, and industry produce more accurate assignments and better rep-account fit" ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_9bbf6ccc a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When implementing a complete lead routing system" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Define routing decision tree (named accounts → ACV tier → PLG → territory → round-robin). 2. Configure round-robin with availability and quota-weighting. 3. Set up territory tables (geography, size, industry). 4. Implement ABM target account list with domain matching. 5. Build speed-to-lead automation with escalation chain. 6. Track weekly metrics (avg/median response time, % within SLA, conversion by response time)." ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

oc:kn_bc0cd846 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building any routing configuration" ;
    oc:directiveContent "All leads must be assigned to either a named rep or a queue with a defined SLA. No lead should remain unassigned without a timer-driven escalation path." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Unassigned leads represent revenue leakage; SLA-bound queues ensure accountability even when individual reps are unavailable" ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_db5510d9 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When setting speed-to-lead SLAs" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Respond to new MQLs within 5 minutes for 21x qualification lift. Implement escalation at 15 min (backup rep), 30 min (manager), 60 min (reassignment)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Lead Connect and InsideSales.com data shows dramatic conversion drop-off after 5 minutes; structured escalation prevents leads from going cold" ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

